Date: Tue, 25 Aug 1998 15:59:16 +0100
From: Arthur King <art.king@cableol.co.uk>

May I cheat a little and address this answer to the question of protection
of staff vaccinated with Fuenzalida-Palacios vaccine against risk of rabies
through an increase in the number of vampire and also non-vampire cases
handled and/or submitted to the laboratory? I am cheating because I cannot
give a definitive answer, but I would like to say Hallo to Phyllis, a
friend of long standing, and also to pass the question to Alex Wandeler in
Canada, who may not only be able to give a better answer but whom I believe
may be interested in looking at the genetics of some of the
non-haematophagous bat viruses.
The first point I would make is that Phyllis says that she and her staff
"used to have antibody level checked every year". Does this mean that it is
no longer tested? If that is the case, I would suggest having antibody
level measured as soon as possible and then every six months and boost when
the titre falls to 0.5IU.
The second point I would make is that I believe diploid cell vaccine to be
superior to all others BUT I do not know what the consequence of following
F-P vaccine with HDCV would be, perhaps Alex may be able to answer.
I also copy this to Paulo Roehe, another old friend, who may also be
interested in the genetics of the non-haematophagous bat viruses.
So, forgive me please for cheating, but I've done my best!
--
Arthur King
e-mail: art.king@cableol.co.uk
