[3]
Date: Wed, 26 Aug 1998 13:11:49 -0600 (CST)
From: Rodney Rohde <Rodney.Rohde@tdh.state.tx.us>

Rabies in bats has caused increased levels of interest, with respect to
both pre and post-exposure treatment, due to the level of human rabies
deaths associated with documented or suspect bat exposure. At the Texas
Department of Health, laboratory personnel and others working in high risk
areas with bats (or any suspect rabid specimen) have their antibody level
checked every year. A booster is given when the titer is lower than 0.5 IU.
0.5 international units of neutralizing antibody is considered by WHO as
evidence of adequate pre-exposure immunization regardless of the vaccine or
route. New generation high potency vaccines may elicit higher antibody
titers and immunize a higher percentage of recipients with fewer side
effects than do mouse brain vaccines, but 0.5 iu is still an adequate
response. Furthermore, there is no evidence that those persons immunized
with newer vaccines and maintaining 0.5 iu of antibody are protected
against a broader range of rabies viruses or non-rabies lyssavirus than
those immunized with mouse brain vaccines and maintaining 0.5 iu of
antibody. One could even argue the converse (with no supporting data,
however), since there are three different rabies viruses included in the
seed virus for the mouse brain vaccine while only one rabies virus is used
as the seed virus for the new generation vaccines. Booster immunizations
are necessary for all pre-immunized persons exposed to rabies virus or
non-rabies lyssaviruses, regardless of pre-exposure immunization.
--
Rodney E. Rohde, MS
Molecular Epidemiologist
Texas Dept. of Health
Zoonosis Control
1100 W. 49th St.
Austin, Tx 78756
(512)-458-7255
